com.inqwell.any

Class InstanceHierarchyMap

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.inqwell.any.AbstractComposite
      • com.inqwell.any.AbstractMap
        • com.inqwell.any.PropertyAccessMap
          • com.inqwell.any.AnyMap
            • com.inqwell.any.AnyPMap
              • com.inqwell.any.InstanceHierarchyMap
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    Any, Composite, EventGenerator, EventListener, Map, Orderable, Vectored, Serializable, Cloneable
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    AbstractProcess, AnyView, BasicProcess.RootMap

    public class InstanceHierarchyMap
extends AnyPMap
implements Map, EventGenerator, EventListener, Vectored, Orderable
    The Map implementation used to build structures of managed objects within the Any server through which events can propagate. Children implementing the EventGenerator interface have this map establishing itself as an event listener on that child. By composing structures of InstanceHierarchyMaps a client can listen for events at some node which eminated from somewhere within the structure rooted at that node. The event parameter at any point is established on the event. Typically, instances of class NodeEvent are propagated and as this class prepends each argument passed to Event.setParameter(), the event carries a node specification which could be applied at that point to locate the source of the event.

    The anticipated thread model for the use of this class is that the owner thread will inspect and mutate the it, use LocateNode and so forth, while possibly other threads will call processEvent (and therefore fireEvent). The synchronization issues surrounding these aspects are handled by this class. Otherwise there are no special synchronization considerations over other implementations.

    The hashCode() method operates identity semantics without being wrapped inside an identity decorator. This is because this implementation is complicated with the EventGenerator/Listener interfaces and we are not interested in comparisons with value semantics which would propagate the evaluation of the hash code to whatever depth the structure was.
